Chapter 2: The Speed's Price
Finn knew he couldn't use his newfound Super Speed inside the Guild Compound.
If any sensor or any high-tier hunter—especially someone like Silas—caught even a glimpse of a silver blur streaking through the halls, his secret would be stripped bare. In Sector Seven, an unregistered power wasn't a miracle; it was a death sentence.
He waited until the dead of night, when the only sounds were the distant hum of the atmospheric filters and the steady, rhythmic snoring of the other provisionals in the barracks. He slipped away, moving through the city’s industrial decay until he reached the forgotten Hydro-Conduits—massive, hollow concrete tunnels buried deep beneath the old district.
The First Test
The tunnel was a kilometer of unbroken darkness, smelling of damp concrete and ancient rust. It was the only place where he could run without being seen.
Finn stood at the entrance, his heart hammering against his ribs. He focused on the silver energy coiled in his marrow, the cold "Inheritance" he had stolen from the Viper. He pushed the feeling of speed into his legs and lunged forward.
He was fast—faster than any human had a right to be—but it was clumsy. His muscles fought the sudden, explosive force. Every step felt like a controlled explosion that his brain couldn't quite time. He stopped after only fifty meters, his lungs burning and his legs trembling.
This is not enough, the cold, sharp voice from the shard seemed to echo in his mind. Move. Run. Never stop.
Finn realized the power wasn't just a physical switch. To unlock the full Tier 2 speed, he had to stop thinking like a human and start thinking like a predator.
The Silver Blur
He tried again. This time, he didn't fight the aggressive, restless energy. He embraced the instinct of the Kinetic Viper: the singular, mindless urge to close the distance between itself and its prey.
He pushed the energy into his core and exploded.
The world stretched. The damp walls became grey, vibrating smears. The wind didn't just whistle; it screamed in his ears, tearing at his hair. Finn wasn't running anymore; he was a thin, shimmering silver blur cutting through the dark.
He reached the full speed of the Viper, his body moving faster than his human eyes could process.
But as the end of the tunnel approached, he realized the terrifying price of the instinct. The monster's mind, now driving his muscles, rejected the very concept of "stopping." When Finn tried to decelerate, the raw momentum resisted him. His focus shattered.
He slammed into the curved concrete wall at forty miles per hour.
The Price of Power
Finn lay on the cold floor, the echo of the Viper's aggression fading into a dull, throbbing ache. He gasped for air, his vision swimming. His suit was scuffed and torn at the elbow, and the copper taste of blood filled his mouth.
He sat up slowly, examining the damage. The physical pain was manageable, but the internal realization was far worse.
"The Shard is part of my mind now," Finn muttered, his voice echoing in the hollow tunnel. "To use the power, I have to let the monster drive. And the monster doesn't know how to stop."
He looked down the dark conduit. He had scavenged the strength he craved, but he had also invited a second, reckless mind into his own head. He wasn't just training his legs; he was going to have to fight a mental war every time he stepped onto the battlefield.
Finn knew this wouldn't be a quick victory. Mastering the silver speed—and the predatory mind that came with it—would take months of secluded, agonizing practice. His journey to becoming the strongest had just become a battle for his own thoughts.
